# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: regex
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:regex/character-classes] Character classes distinguish kinds of characters such as, for example, distinguishing between letters and digits.
[src:regex/character-classes] In this example, we match a sequence of 4 digits with `\d{4}`.
[src:regex/character-classes] `\b` indicates a word boundary (i.e., do not start or end matching in the middle of a number sequence).
[src:regex/character-classes] See more examples in the character class escape reference.
[src:regex/character-classes] In this example, we match a word starting with the letter A.
[src:regex/character-classes] `\b` indicates a word boundary (i.e., do not start matching in the middle of a word).
[src:regex/character-classes] `\w+` indicates any character *from the Latin alphabet*, multiple times (`+` is a quantifier).
[src:regex/character-classes] Note that because we already match until there are no more word characters, an end `\b` boundary is not necessary.
[src:regex/character-classes] Instead of the Latin alphabet, we can use a range of Unicode characters to identify a word (thus being able to deal with text in other languages like Russian or Arabic).
[src:regex/character-classes] The "Basic Multilingual Plane" of Unicode contains most of the characters used around the world and we can use character classes and ranges to match words written with those characters.
[src:regex/character-classes] See more examples in the Unicode character class escape reference.
[src:regex/character-classes] In this example, we count the number of vowels (A, E, I, O, U, Y) in a text.
[src:regex/character-classes] The `g` flag is used to match all occurrences of the pattern in the text.
[src:regex/character-classes] The `i` flag is used to make the pattern case-insensitive, so it matches both uppercase and lowercase vowels.
[src:regex/groups-and-backreferences] Groups group multiple patterns as a whole, and capturing groups provide extra submatch information when using a regular expression pattern to match against a string.
[src:regex/groups-and-backreferences] Backreferences refer to a previously captured group in the same regular expression.
[src:regex/groups-and-backreferences] In this example, we match two words in a structured format by using capturing groups to remember them.
[src:regex/groups-and-backreferences] `\w+` matches one or more word characters, and the parentheses `()` create a capturing group.
[src:regex/groups-and-backreferences] The `g` flag is used to match all occurrences.
[src:regex/groups-and-backreferences] See more examples in the capturing group reference.
[src:regex/groups-and-backreferences] This example is the same as above, but we use named capturing groups to remember the matched words instead.
[src:regex/groups-and-backreferences] This way, we can access the matched words by their meanings.
[src:regex/groups-and-backreferences] See more examples in the named capturing group reference.
[src:regex/groups-and-backreferences] In this example, we first match a single or double quote character with `['"]`, remember it, match an arbitrary number of characters with `.*?` (`*?` is a non-greedy quantifier), until we match the remembered quote character again with `\1`.
[src:regex/groups-and-backreferences] The `\1` is a backreference to the first capturing group, which matches the same type of quote.
[src:regex/groups-and-backreferences] The result will therefore be two strings: `"'"` and `'"'`.
[src:regex/groups-and-backreferences] See more examples in the backreference reference.
[src:regex/groups-and-backreferences] By providing the `d` flag, the indices of each capturing group is returned.
[src:regex/groups-and-backreferences] This is especially useful if you are correlating each matched group with the original text — for example, to provide compiler diagnostics.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Regular expressions (called REs, or regexes, or regex patterns) are essentially a tiny, highly specialized programming language embedded inside Python and made available through the `re` module.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Using this little language, you specify the rules for the set of possible strings that you want to match; this set might contain English sentences, or e-mail addresses, or TeX commands, or anything you like.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] You can then ask questions such as “Does this string match the pattern?”, or “Is there a match for the pattern anywhere in this string?”.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] You can also use REs to modify a string or to split it apart in various ways.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Regular expression patterns are compiled into a series of bytecodes which are then executed by a matching engine written in C.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] For advanced use, it may be necessary to pay careful attention to how the engine will execute a given RE, and write the RE in a certain way in order to produce bytecode that runs faster.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Optimization isn’t covered in this document, because it requires that you have a good understanding of the matching engine’s internals.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The regular expression language is relatively small and restricted, so not all possible string processing tasks can be done using regular expressions.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] There are also tasks that *can* be done with regular expressions, but the expressions turn out to be very complicated.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] In these cases, you may be better off writing Python code to do the processing; while Python code will be slower than an elaborate regular expression, it will also probably be more understandable.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] We’ll start by learning about the simplest possible regular expressions.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Since regular expressions are used to operate on strings, we’ll begin with the most common task: matching characters.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] For a detailed explanation of the computer science underlying regular expressions (deterministic and non-deterministic finite automata), you can refer to almost any textbook on writing compilers.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Most letters and characters will simply match themselves.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] For example, the regular expression `test` will match the string `test` exactly.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] There are exceptions to this rule; some characters are special *metacharacters*, and don’t match themselves.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Instead, they signal that some out-of-the-ordinary thing should be matched, or they affect other portions of the RE by repeating them or changing their meaning.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Much of this document is devoted to discussing various metacharacters and what they do.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Here’s a complete list of the metacharacters; their meanings will be discussed in the rest of this HOWTO.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The first metacharacters we’ll look at are `[` and `]`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] They’re used for specifying a character class, which is a set of characters that you wish to match.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Characters can be listed individually, or a range of characters can be indicated by giving two characters and separating them by a `'-'`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] For example, `[abc]` will match any of the characters `a`, `b`, or `c`; this is the same as `[a-c]`, which uses a range to express the same set of characters.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] If you wanted to match only lowercase letters, your RE would be `[a-z]`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Metacharacters (except `\`) are not active inside classes.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] For example, `[akm$]` will match any of the characters `'a'`, `'k'`, `'m'`, or `'$'`; `'$'` is usually a metacharacter, but inside a character class it’s stripped of its special nature.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] You can match the characters not listed within the class by *complementing* the set.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] This is indicated by including a `'^'` as the first character of the class.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] For example, `[^5]` will match any character except `'5'`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] If the caret appears elsewhere in a character class, it does not have special meaning.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Perhaps the most important metacharacter is the backslash, `\`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] As in Python string literals, the backslash can be followed by various characters to signal various special sequences.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] It’s also used to escape all the metacharacters so you can still match them in patterns; for example, if you need to match a `[` or `\`, you can precede them with a backslash to remove their special meaning: `\[` or `\\`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Some of the special sequences beginning with `'\'` represent predefined sets of characters that are often useful, such as the set of digits, the set of letters, or the set of anything that isn’t whitespace.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Let’s take an example: `\w` matches any alphanumeric character.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] If the regex pattern is expressed in bytes, this is equivalent to the class `[a-zA-Z0-9_]`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] If the regex pattern is a string, `\w` will match all the characters marked as letters in the Unicode database provided by the `unicodedata` module.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] You can use the more restricted definition of `\w` in a string pattern by supplying the `re.ASCII` flag when compiling the regular expression.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The following list of special sequences isn’t complete.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] For a complete list of sequences and expanded class definitions for Unicode string patterns, see the last part of Regular Expression Syntax in the Standard Library reference.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] In general, the Unicode versions match any character that’s in the appropriate category in the Unicode database.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Matches any decimal digit; this is equivalent to the class `[0-9]`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Matches any non-digit character; this is equivalent to the class `[^0-9]`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Matches any whitespace character; this is equivalent to the class `[ \t\n\r\f\v]`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Matches any non-whitespace character; this is equivalent to the class `[^ \t\n\r\f\v]`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Matches any alphanumeric character; this is equivalent to the class `[a-zA-Z0-9_]`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Matches any non-alphanumeric character; this is equivalent to the class `[^a-zA-Z0-9_]`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] These sequences can be included inside a character class.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] For example, `[\s,.]` is a character class that will match any whitespace character, or `','` or `'.'`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The final metacharacter in this section is `.`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] It matches anything except a newline character, and there’s an alternate mode (`re.DOTALL`) where it will match even a newline.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] `.` is often used where you want to match “any character”.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Being able to match varying sets of characters is the first thing regular expressions can do that isn’t already possible with the methods available on strings.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] However, if that was the only additional capability of regexes, they wouldn’t be much of an advance.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Another capability is that you can specify that portions of the RE must be repeated a certain number of times.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The first metacharacter for repeating things that we’ll look at is `*`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] `*` doesn’t match the literal character `'*'`; instead, it specifies that the previous character can be matched zero or more times, instead of exactly once.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Repetitions such as `*` are *greedy*; when repeating a RE, the matching engine will try to repeat it as many times as possible.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] If later portions of the pattern don’t match, the matching engine will then back up and try again with fewer repetitions.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] A step-by-step example will make this more obvious.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Let’s consider the expression `a[bcd]*b`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] This matches the letter `'a'`, zero or more letters from the class `[bcd]`, and finally ends with a `'b'`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Now imagine matching this RE against the string `'abcbd'`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The end of the RE has now been reached, and it has matched `'abcb'`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] This demonstrates how the matching engine goes as far as it can at first, and if no match is found it will then progressively back up and retry the rest of the RE again and again.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] It will back up until it has tried zero matches for `[bcd]*`, and if that subsequently fails, the engine will conclude that the string doesn’t match the RE at all.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Another repeating metacharacter is `+`, which matches one or more times.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Pay careful attention to the difference between `*` and `+`; `*` matches *zero* or more times, so whatever’s being repeated may not be present at all, while `+` requires at least *one* occurrence.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] There are two more repeating operators or quantifiers.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The question mark character, `?`, matches either once or zero times; you can think of it as marking something as being optional.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] For example, `home-?brew` matches either `'homebrew'` or `'home-brew'`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The most complicated quantifier is `{m,n}`, where *m* and *n* are decimal integers.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] This quantifier means there must be at least *m* repetitions, and at most *n*.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] It won’t match `'ab'`, which has no slashes, or `'a////b'`, which has four.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] You can omit either *m* or *n*; in that case, a reasonable value is assumed for the missing value.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Omitting *m* is interpreted as a lower limit of 0, while omitting *n* results in an upper bound of infinity.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The simplest case `{m}` matches the preceding item exactly *m* times.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Readers of a reductionist bent may notice that the three other quantifiers can all be expressed using this notation.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] It’s better to use `*`, `+`, or `?` when you can, simply because they’re shorter and easier to read.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Now that we’ve looked at some simple regular expressions, how do we actually use them in Python?
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The `re` module provides an interface to the regular expression engine, allowing you to compile REs into objects and then perform matches with them.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Regular expressions are compiled into pattern objects, which have methods for various operations such as searching for pattern matches or performing string substitutions.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] `re.compile()` also accepts an optional *flags* argument, used to enable various special features and syntax variations.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The RE is passed to `re.compile()` as a string.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] REs are handled as strings because regular expressions aren’t part of the core Python language, and no special syntax was created for expressing them.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] (There are applications that don’t need REs at all, so there’s no need to bloat the language specification by including them.) Instead, the `re` module is simply a C extension module included with Python, just like the `socket` or `zlib` modules.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Putting REs in strings keeps the Python language simpler, but has one disadvantage which is the topic of the next section.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] As stated earlier, regular expressions use the backslash character (`'\'`) to indicate special forms or to allow special characters to be used without invoking their special meaning.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] This conflicts with Python’s usage of the same character for the same purpose in string literals.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Let’s say you want to write a RE that matches the string `\section`, which might be found in a LaTeX file.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] To figure out what to write in the program code, start with the desired string to be matched.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Next, you must escape any backslashes and other metacharacters by preceding them with a backslash, resulting in the string `\\section`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The resulting string that must be passed to `re.compile()` must be `\\section`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] However, to express this as a Python string literal, both backslashes must be escaped *again*.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] In short, to match a literal backslash, one has to write `'\\\\'` as the RE string, because the regular expression must be `\\`, and each backslash must be expressed as `\\` inside a regular Python string literal.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] In REs that feature backslashes repeatedly, this leads to lots of repeated backslashes and makes the resulting strings difficult to understand.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The solution is to use Python’s raw string notation for regular expressions; backslashes are not handled in any special way in a string literal prefixed with `'r'`, so `r"\n"` is a two-character string containing `'\'` and `'n'`, while `"\n"` is a one-character string containing a newline.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Regular expressions will often be written in Python code using this raw string notation.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] In addition, special escape sequences that are valid in regular expressions, but not valid as Python string literals, now result in a `SyntaxWarning` and will eventually become a `SyntaxError`, which means the sequences will be invalid if raw string notation or escaping the backslashes isn’t used.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Once you have an object representing a compiled regular expression, what do you do with it?
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Pattern objects have several methods and attributes.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Only the most significant ones will be covered here; consult the `re` docs for a complete listing.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] `match()` and `search()` return `None` if no match can be found.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] If they’re successful, a match object instance is returned, containing information about the match: where it starts and ends, the substring it matched, and more.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] You can learn about this by interactively experimenting with the `re` module.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] This HOWTO uses the standard Python interpreter for its examples.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Now, you can try matching various strings against the RE `[a-z]+`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] An empty string shouldn’t match at all, since `+` means ‘one or more repetitions’.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] `match()` should return `None` in this case, which will cause the interpreter to print no output.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] You can explicitly print the result of `match()` to make this clear.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Now, let’s try it on a string that it should match, such as `tempo`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] In this case, `match()` will return a match object, so you should store the result in a variable for later use.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Now you can query the match object for information about the matching string.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] `group()` returns the substring that was matched by the RE.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] `start()` and `end()` return the starting and ending index of the match.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] `span()` returns both start and end indexes in a single tuple.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Since the `match()` method only checks if the RE matches at the start of a string, `start()` will always be zero.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] However, the `search()` method of patterns scans through the string, so the match may not start at zero in that case.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] In actual programs, the most common style is to store the match object in a variable, and then check if it was `None`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Two pattern methods return all of the matches for a pattern.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The `r` prefix, making the literal a raw string literal, is needed in this example because escape sequences in a normal “cooked” string literal that are not recognized by Python, as opposed to regular expressions, now result in a `SyntaxWarning` and will eventually become a `SyntaxError`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] `findall()` has to create the entire list before it can be returned as the result.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] You don’t have to create a pattern object and call its methods; the `re` module also provides top-level functions called `match()`, `search()`, `findall()`, `sub()`, and so forth.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] These functions take the same arguments as the corresponding pattern method with the RE string added as the first argument, and still return either `None` or a match object instance.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Under the hood, these functions simply create a pattern object for you and call the appropriate method on it.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] They also store the compiled object in a cache, so future calls using the same RE won’t need to parse the pattern again and again.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Should you use these module-level functions, or should you get the pattern and call its methods yourself?
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] If you’re accessing a regex within a loop, pre-compiling it will save a few function calls.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Outside of loops, there’s not much difference thanks to the internal cache.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Compilation flags let you modify some aspects of how regular expressions work.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Flags are available in the `re` module under two names, a long name such as `IGNORECASE` and a short, one-letter form such as `I`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] (If you’re familiar with Perl’s pattern modifiers, the one-letter forms use the same letters; the short form of `re.VERBOSE` is `re.X`, for example.) Multiple flags can be specified by bitwise OR-ing them; `re.I | re.M` sets both the `I` and `M` flags, for example.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Here’s a table of the available flags, followed by a more detailed explanation of each one.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Perform case-insensitive matching; character class and literal strings will match letters by ignoring case.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] For example, `[A-Z]` will match lowercase letters, too.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Full Unicode matching also works unless the `ASCII` flag is used to disable non-ASCII matches.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] `Spam` will match `'Spam'`, `'spam'`, `'spAM'`, or `'ſpam'` (the latter is matched only in Unicode mode).
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] This lowercasing doesn’t take the current locale into account; it will if you also set the `LOCALE` flag.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Make `\w`, `\W`, `\b`, `\B` and case-insensitive matching dependent on the current locale instead of the Unicode database.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Locales are a feature of the C library intended to help in writing programs that take account of language differences.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] For example, if you’re processing encoded French text, you’d want to be able to write `\w+` to match words, but `\w` only matches the character class `[A-Za-z]` in bytes patterns; it won’t match bytes corresponding to `é` or `ç`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] If your system is configured properly and a French locale is selected, certain C functions will tell the program that the byte corresponding to `é` should also be considered a letter.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Setting the `LOCALE` flag when compiling a regular expression will cause the resulting compiled object to use these C functions for `\w`; this is slower, but also enables `\w+` to match French words as you’d expect.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The use of this flag is discouraged in Python 3 as the locale mechanism is very unreliable, it only handles one “culture” at a time, and it only works with 8-bit locales.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Unicode matching is already enabled by default in Python 3 for Unicode (str) patterns, and it is able to handle different locales/languages.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Usually `^` matches only at the beginning of the string, and `$` matches only at the end of the string and immediately before the newline (if any) at the end of the string.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] When this flag is specified, `^` matches at the beginning of the string and at the beginning of each line within the string, immediately following each newline.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Similarly, the `$` metacharacter matches either at the end of the string and at the end of each line (immediately preceding each newline).
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Makes the `'.'` special character match any character at all, including a newline; without this flag, `'.'` will match anything *except* a newline.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Make `\w`, `\W`, `\b`, `\B`, `\s` and `\S` perform ASCII-only matching instead of full Unicode matching.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] This is only meaningful for Unicode patterns, and is ignored for byte patterns.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] This flag allows you to write regular expressions that are more readable by granting you more flexibility in how you can format them.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] When this flag has been specified, whitespace within the RE string is ignored, except when the whitespace is in a character class or preceded by an unescaped backslash; this lets you organize and indent the RE more clearly.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] This flag also lets you put comments within a RE that will be ignored by the engine; comments are marked by a `'#'` that’s neither in a character class nor preceded by an unescaped backslash.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] For example, here’s a RE that uses `re.VERBOSE`; see how much easier it is to read?
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] In the above example, Python’s automatic concatenation of string literals has been used to break up the RE into smaller pieces, but it’s still more difficult to understand than the version using `re.VERBOSE`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] So far we’ve only covered a part of the features of regular expressions.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] In this section, we’ll cover some new metacharacters, and how to use groups to retrieve portions of the text that was matched.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] There are some metacharacters that we haven’t covered yet.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Most of them will be covered in this section.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Some of the remaining metacharacters to be discussed are *zero-width assertions*.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] They don’t cause the engine to advance through the string; instead, they consume no characters at all, and simply succeed or fail.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] For example, `\b` is an assertion that the current position is located at a word boundary; the position isn’t changed by the `\b` at all.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] This means that zero-width assertions should never be repeated, because if they match once at a given location, they can obviously be matched an infinite number of times.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] If *A* and *B* are regular expressions, `A|B` will match any string that matches either *A* or *B*.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] `|` has very low precedence in order to make it work reasonably when you’re alternating multi-character strings.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] To match a literal `'|'`, use `\|`, or enclose it inside a character class, as in `[|]`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Unless the `MULTILINE` flag has been set, this will only match at the beginning of the string.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] In `MULTILINE` mode, this also matches immediately after each newline within the string.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] For example, if you wish to match the word `From` only at the beginning of a line, the RE to use is `^From`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Matches at the end of a line, which is defined as either the end of the string, or any location followed by a newline character.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] To match a literal `'$'`, use `\$` or enclose it inside a character class, as in `[$]`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Matches only at the start of the string.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] When not in `MULTILINE` mode, `\A` and `^` are effectively the same.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] In `MULTILINE` mode, they’re different: `\A` still matches only at the beginning of the string, but `^` may match at any location inside the string that follows a newline character.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] For compatibility with old Python versions.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] This is a zero-width assertion that matches only at the beginning or end of a word.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] A word is defined as a sequence of alphanumeric characters, so the end of a word is indicated by whitespace or a non-alphanumeric character.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The following example matches `class` only when it’s a complete word; it won’t match when it’s contained inside another word.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] There are two subtleties you should remember when using this special sequence.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] First, this is the worst collision between Python’s string literals and regular expression sequences.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] In Python’s string literals, `\b` is the backspace character, ASCII value 8.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] If you’re not using raw strings, then Python will convert the `\b` to a backspace, and your RE won’t match as you expect it to.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The following example looks the same as our previous RE, but omits the `'r'` in front of the RE string.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Second, inside a character class, where there’s no use for this assertion, `\b` represents the backspace character, for compatibility with Python’s string literals.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Another zero-width assertion, this is the opposite of `\b`, only matching when the current position is not at a word boundary.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Frequently you need to obtain more information than just whether the RE matched or not.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Regular expressions are often used to dissect strings by writing a RE divided into several subgroups which match different components of interest.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] This can be handled by writing a regular expression which matches an entire header line, and has one group which matches the header name, and another group which matches the header’s value.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Groups are marked by the `'('`, `')'` metacharacters.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] `'('` and `')'` have much the same meaning as they do in mathematical expressions; they group together the expressions contained inside them, and you can repeat the contents of a group with a quantifier, such as `*`, `+`, `?`, or `{m,n}`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] For example, `(ab)*` will match zero or more repetitions of `ab`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Groups indicated with `'('`, `')'` also capture the starting and ending index of the text that they match; this can be retrieved by passing an argument to `group()`, `start()`, `end()`, and `span()`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Group 0 is always present; it’s the whole RE, so match object methods all have group 0 as their default argument.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Later we’ll see how to express groups that don’t capture the span of text that they match.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Subgroups are numbered from left to right, from 1 upward.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Groups can be nested; to determine the number, just count the opening parenthesis characters, going from left to right.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] `group()` can be passed multiple group numbers at a time, in which case it will return a tuple containing the corresponding values for those groups.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The `groups()` method returns a tuple containing the strings for all the subgroups, from 1 up to however many there are.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Backreferences in a pattern allow you to specify that the contents of an earlier capturing group must also be found at the current location in the string.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] For example, `\1` will succeed if the exact contents of group 1 can be found at the current position, and fails otherwise.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Remember that Python’s string literals also use a backslash followed by numbers to allow including arbitrary characters in a string, so be sure to use a raw string when incorporating backreferences in a RE.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] For example, the following RE detects doubled words in a string.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Backreferences like this aren’t often useful for just searching through a string — there are few text formats which repeat data in this way — but you’ll soon find out that they’re *very* useful when performing string substitutions.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Elaborate REs may use many groups, both to capture substrings of interest, and to group and structure the RE itself.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] In complex REs, it becomes difficult to keep track of the group numbers.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] There are two features which help with this problem.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Both of them use a common syntax for regular expression extensions, so we’ll look at that first.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Perl 5 is well known for its powerful additions to standard regular expressions.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] For these new features the Perl developers couldn’t choose new single-keystroke metacharacters or new special sequences beginning with `\` without making Perl’s regular expressions confusingly different from standard REs.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] If they chose `&` as a new metacharacter, for example, old expressions would be assuming that `&` was a regular character and wouldn’t have escaped it by writing `\&` or `[&]`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The solution chosen by the Perl developers was to use `(?...)` as the extension syntax.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] `?` immediately after a parenthesis was a syntax error because the `?` would have nothing to repeat, so this didn’t introduce any compatibility problems.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The characters immediately after the `?` indicate what extension is being used, so `(?=foo)` is one thing (a positive lookahead assertion) and `(?:foo)` is something else (a non-capturing group containing the subexpression `foo`).
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Python supports several of Perl’s extensions and adds an extension syntax to Perl’s extension syntax.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] If the first character after the question mark is a `P`, you know that it’s an extension that’s specific to Python.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Now that we’ve looked at the general extension syntax, we can return to the features that simplify working with groups in complex REs.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Sometimes you’ll want to use a group to denote a part of a regular expression, but aren’t interested in retrieving the group’s contents.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] You can make this fact explicit by using a non-capturing group: `(?:...)`, where you can replace the `...` with any other regular expression.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] `(?:...)` is particularly useful when modifying an existing pattern, since you can add new groups without changing how all the other groups are numbered.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] It should be mentioned that there’s no performance difference in searching between capturing and non-capturing groups; neither form is any faster than the other.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] A more significant feature is named groups: instead of referring to them by numbers, groups can be referenced by a name.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The syntax for a named group is one of the Python-specific extensions: `(?P<name>...)`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] *name* is, obviously, the name of the group.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Named groups behave exactly like capturing groups, and additionally associate a name with a group.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The match object methods that deal with capturing groups all accept either integers that refer to the group by number or strings that contain the desired group’s name.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Named groups are handy because they let you use easily remembered names, instead of having to remember numbers.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] It’s obviously much easier to retrieve `m.group('zonem')`, instead of having to remember to retrieve group 9.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The syntax for backreferences in an expression such as `(...)\1` refers to the number of the group.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] There’s naturally a variant that uses the group name instead of the number.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] This is another Python extension: `(?P=name)` indicates that the contents of the group called *name* should again be matched at the current point.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Another zero-width assertion is the lookahead assertion.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] This succeeds if the contained regular expression, represented here by `...`, successfully matches at the current location, and fails otherwise.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] But, once the contained expression has been tried, the matching engine doesn’t advance at all; the rest of the pattern is tried right where the assertion started.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] This is the opposite of the positive assertion; it succeeds if the contained expression *doesn’t* match at the current position in the string.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] To make this concrete, let’s look at a case where a lookahead is useful.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Consider a simple pattern to match a filename and split it apart into a base name and an extension, separated by a `.`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] For example, in `news.rc`, `news` is the base name, and `rc` is the filename’s extension.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Notice that the `.` needs to be treated specially because it’s a metacharacter, so it’s inside a character class to only match that specific character.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Also notice the trailing `$`; this is added to ensure that all the rest of the string must be included in the extension.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] This regular expression matches `foo.bar` and `autoexec.bat` and `sendmail.cf` and `printers.conf`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Now, consider complicating the problem a bit; what if you want to match filenames where the extension is not `bat`?
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The first attempt above tries to exclude `bat` by requiring that the first character of the extension is not a `b`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] This is wrong, because the pattern also doesn’t match `foo.bar`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The expression gets messier when you try to patch up the first solution by requiring one of the following cases to match: the first character of the extension isn’t `b`; the second character isn’t `a`; or the third character isn’t `t`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] This accepts `foo.bar` and rejects `autoexec.bat`, but it requires a three-letter extension and won’t accept a filename with a two-letter extension such as `sendmail.cf`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] We’ll complicate the pattern again in an effort to fix it.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] In the third attempt, the second and third letters are all made optional in order to allow matching extensions shorter than three characters, such as `sendmail.cf`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The pattern’s getting really complicated now, which makes it hard to read and understand.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Worse, if the problem changes and you want to exclude both `bat` and `exe` as extensions, the pattern would get even more complicated and confusing.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The negative lookahead means: if the expression `bat` doesn’t match at this point, try the rest of the pattern; if `bat$` does match, the whole pattern will fail.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The trailing `$` is required to ensure that something like `sample.batch`, where the extension only starts with `bat`, will be allowed.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The `[^.]*` makes sure that the pattern works when there are multiple dots in the filename.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Excluding another filename extension is now easy; simply add it as an alternative inside the assertion.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Up to this point, we’ve simply performed searches against a static string.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The `split()` method of a pattern splits a string apart wherever the RE matches, returning a list of the pieces.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] It’s similar to the `split()` method of strings but provides much more generality in the delimiters that you can split by; string `split()` only supports splitting by whitespace or by a fixed string.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] As you’d expect, there’s a module-level `re.split()` function, too.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Split *string* by the matches of the regular expression.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] If capturing parentheses are used in the RE, then their contents will also be returned as part of the resulting list.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] If *maxsplit* is nonzero, at most *maxsplit* splits are performed.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] You can limit the number of splits made, by passing a value for *maxsplit*.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] When *maxsplit* is nonzero, at most *maxsplit* splits will be made, and the remainder of the string is returned as the final element of the list.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] In the following example, the delimiter is any sequence of non-alphanumeric characters.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] Sometimes you’re not only interested in what the text between delimiters is, but also need to know what the delimiter was.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] If capturing parentheses are used in the RE, then their values are also returned as part of the list.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p01] The module-level function `re.split()` adds the RE to be used as the first argument, but is otherwise the same.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] Regular expressions are a powerful tool for some applications, but in some ways their behaviour isn’t intuitive and at times they don’t behave the way you may expect them to.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] This section will point out some of the most common pitfalls.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] Sometimes using the `re` module is a mistake.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] If you’re matching a fixed string, or a single character class, and you’re not using any `re` features such as the `IGNORECASE` flag, then the full power of regular expressions may not be required.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] Strings have several methods for performing operations with fixed strings and they’re usually much faster, because the implementation is a single small C loop that’s been optimized for the purpose, instead of the large, more generalized regular expression engine.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] One example might be replacing a single fixed string with another one; for example, you might replace `word` with `deed`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] `re.sub()` seems like the function to use for this, but consider the `replace()` method.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] Note that `replace()` will also replace `word` inside words, turning `swordfish` into `sdeedfish`, but the naive RE `word` would have done that, too.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] (To avoid performing the substitution on parts of words, the pattern would have to be `\bword\b`, in order to require that `word` have a word boundary on either side.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] Another common task is deleting every occurrence of a single character from a string or replacing it with another single character.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] You might do this with something like `re.sub('\n', ' ', S)`, but `translate()` is capable of doing both tasks and will be faster than any regular expression operation can be.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] In short, before turning to the `re` module, consider whether your problem can be solved with a faster and simpler string method.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] When repeating a regular expression, as in `a*`, the resulting action is to consume as much of the pattern as possible.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] This fact often bites you when you’re trying to match a pair of balanced delimiters, such as the angle brackets surrounding an HTML tag.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] The naive pattern for matching a single HTML tag doesn’t work because of the greedy nature of `.*`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] The RE matches the `'<'` in `'<html>'`, and the `.*` consumes the rest of the string.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] There’s still more left in the RE, though, and the `>` can’t match at the end of the string, so the regular expression engine has to backtrack character by character until it finds a match for the `>`.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] The final match extends from the `'<'` in `'<html>'` to the `'>'` in `'</title>'`, which isn’t what you want.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] In this case, the solution is to use the non-greedy quantifiers `*?`, `+?`, `??`, or `{m,n}?`, which match as *little* text as possible.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] In the above example, the `'>'` is tried immediately after the first `'<'` matches, and when it fails, the engine advances a character at a time, retrying the `'>'` at every step.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] (Note that parsing HTML or XML with regular expressions is painful.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] Quick-and-dirty patterns will handle common cases, but HTML and XML have special cases that will break the obvious regular expression; by the time you’ve written a regular expression that handles all of the possible cases, the patterns will be *very* complicated.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] By now you’ve probably noticed that regular expressions are a very compact notation, but they’re not terribly readable.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] REs of moderate complexity can become lengthy collections of backslashes, parentheses, and metacharacters, making them difficult to read and understand.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] For such REs, specifying the `re.VERBOSE` flag when compiling the regular expression can be helpful, because it allows you to format the regular expression more clearly.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] The `re.VERBOSE` flag has several effects.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] Whitespace in the regular expression that *isn’t* inside a character class is ignored.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] This means that an expression such as `dog | cat` is equivalent to the less readable `dog|cat`, but `[a b]` will still match the characters `'a'`, `'b'`, or a space.
[src:regex/howto-regex-p02] In addition, you can also put comments inside a RE; comments extend from a `#` character to the next newline.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] A **regular expression** (shortened as **regex** or **regexp**), sometimes referred to as a **rational expression**, is a sequence of characters that specifies a match pattern in text.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Usually such patterns are used by string-searching algorithms for "find" or "find and replace" operations on strings, or for input validation.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Regular expression techniques are developed in theoretical computer science and formal language theory.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The concept of regular expressions began in the 1950s, when the American mathematician Stephen Cole Kleene formalized the concept of a regular language.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] They came into common use with Unix text-processing utilities.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Different syntaxes for writing regular expressions have existed since the 1980s, one being the POSIX standard and another, widely used, being the Perl syntax.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions are used in search engines, in search and replace dialogs of word processors and text editors, in text processing utilities such as sed and AWK, and in lexical analysis.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions are supported in many programming languages.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Library implementations are often called an "engine", and many of these are available for reuse.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions originated in 1951, when mathematician Stephen Cole Kleene described regular languages using his mathematical notation called *regular events*.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] These arose in theoretical computer science, in the subfields of automata theory (models of computation) and the description and classification of formal languages, motivated by Kleene's attempt to describe early artificial neural networks.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions entered popular use from 1968 in two uses: pattern matching in a text editor and lexical analysis in a compiler.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Among the first appearances of regular expressions in program form was when Ken Thompson built Kleene's notation into the editor QED as a means to match patterns in text files.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] For speed, Thompson implemented regular expression matching by just-in-time compilation (JIT) to IBM 7094 code on the Compatible Time-Sharing System, an important early example of JIT compilation.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Around the same time that Thompson developed QED, a group of researchers including Douglas T.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Ross implemented a tool based on regular expressions that is used for lexical analysis in compiler design.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Many variations of these original forms of regular expressions were used in Unix programs at Bell Labs in the 1970s, including lex, sed, AWK, and expr, and in other programs such as vi, and Emacs (which has its own, incompatible syntax and behavior).
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Regexes were subsequently adopted by a wide range of programs, with these early forms standardized in the POSIX.2 standard in 1992.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] In the 1980s, the more complicated regexes arose in Perl, which originally derived from a regex library written by Henry Spencer (1986), who later wrote an implementation for Tcl called *Advanced Regular Expressions*.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The Tcl library is a hybrid NFA/DFA implementation with improved performance characteristics.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Software projects that have adopted Spencer's Tcl regular expression implementation include PostgreSQL.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Perl later expanded on Spencer's original library to add many new features.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Part of the effort in the design of Raku (formerly named Perl 6) is to improve Perl's regex integration, and to increase their scope and capabilities to allow the definition of parsing expression grammars.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The result is a mini-language called Raku rules, which are used to define Raku grammar as well as provide a tool to programmers in the language.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] These rules maintain existing features of Perl 5.x regexes, but also allow BNF-style definition of a recursive descent parser via sub-rules.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The use of regexes in structured information standards for document and database modeling started in the 1960s and expanded in the 1980s when industry standards like ISO SGML (precursored by ANSI "GCA 101-1983") consolidated.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The kernel of the structure specification language standards consists of regexes.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Its use is evident in the DTD element group syntax.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Prior to the use of regular expressions, many search languages allowed simple wildcards, for example "*" to match any sequence of characters, and "?" to match a single character.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Relics of this can be found today in the glob syntax for filenames, and in the SQL `LIKE` operator.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Starting in 1997, Philip Hazel developed PCRE (Perl Compatible Regular Expressions), which attempts to closely mimic Perl's regex functionality and is used by many modern tools including PHP and Apache HTTP Server.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Today, regexes are widely supported in programming languages, text processing programs (particularly lexers), advanced text editors, and some other programs.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Regex support is part of the standard library of many programming languages, including Java and Python, and is built into the syntax of others, including Perl and ECMAScript.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The phrase *regular expressions*, or *regexes*, is often used to mean the specific, standard textual syntax for representing patterns for matching text, as distinct from the mathematical notation described below.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Each character in a regular expression (that is, each character in the string describing its pattern) is either a metacharacter, having a special meaning, or a regular character that has a literal meaning.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] For example, in the regex `b.`, 'b' is a literal character that matches just 'b', while '.' is a metacharacter that matches every character except a newline.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Therefore, this regex matches, for example, 'b%', or 'bx', or 'b5'.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Together, metacharacters and literal characters can be used to identify text of a given pattern or process a number of instances of it.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Pattern matches may vary from a precise equality to a very general similarity, as controlled by the metacharacters.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] For example, `.` is a very general pattern, `[a-z]` (match all lowercase letters from 'a' to 'z') is less general and `b` is a precise pattern (matches just 'b').
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The metacharacter syntax is designed specifically to represent prescribed targets in a concise and flexible way to direct the automation of text processing of a variety of input data, in a form easy to type using a standard ASCII keyboard.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] A very simple case of a regular expression in this syntax is to locate a word spelled two different ways in a text editor; for example, the regular expression `seriali[sz]e` matches both "serialise" and "serialize".
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Wildcard characters also achieve this, but are more limited in what they can pattern, as they have fewer metacharacters and a simple language-base.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The usual context of wildcard characters is in globbing similar names in a list of files, whereas regexes are usually employed in applications that pattern-match text strings in general.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] For example, the regex `^[ \t]+|[ \t]+$` matches excess whitespace at the beginning or end of a line.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] A **regex processor** translates a regular expression in the above syntax into an internal representation that can be executed and matched against a string representing the text being searched in.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] One possible approach is the Thompson's construction algorithm to construct a nondeterministic finite automaton (NFA), which is then made deterministic and the resulting deterministic finite automaton (DFA) is run on the target text string to recognize substrings that match the regular expression.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The picture shows the NFA scheme `*N*(*s**)` obtained from the regular expression `*s**`, where *s* denotes a simpler regular expression in turn, which has already been recursively translated to the NFA *N*(*s*).
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] A regular expression, often called a *pattern*, specifies a set of strings required for a particular purpose.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] A simple way to specify a finite set of strings is to list its elements or members.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] However, there are often more concise ways: for example, the set containing the three strings "Handel", "Händel", and "Haendel" can be specified by the pattern `H(ä|ae?)ndel`; we say that this pattern *matches* each of the three strings.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] However, there can be many ways to write a regular expression for the same set of strings: for example, `(Hän|Han|Haen)del` also specifies the same set of three strings in this example.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Most formalisms provide the following operations to construct regular expressions.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] are equivalent patterns which both describe the set of "gray" or "grey".
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] , character, or group) specifies how many times the preceding element is allowed to repeat.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] matches any string that contains an "a", and then any character and then "b".
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] matches any string that contains an "a", and then the character "b" at some later point.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] These constructions can be combined to form arbitrarily complex expressions, much like one can construct arithmetical expressions from numbers and the operations +, −, ×, and ÷.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The precise syntax for regular expressions varies among tools and with context; more detail is given in § Syntax.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions describe regular languages in formal language theory.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] They have the same expressive power as regular grammars.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] But the language of regular expressions itself, is context-free language.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions consist of constants, which denote sets of strings, and operator symbols, which denote operations over these sets.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The following definition is standard, and found as such in most textbooks on formal language theory.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] To avoid parentheses, it is assumed that the Kleene star has the highest priority followed by concatenation, then alternation.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] If there is no ambiguity, then parentheses may be omitted.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] For example, `(ab)c` can be written as `abc`, and `a|(b(c*))` can be written as `a|bc*`.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Many textbooks use the symbols ∪, +, or ∨ for alternation instead of the vertical bar.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The derivative of a regular expression can be defined using the Brzozowski derivative.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The formal definition of regular expressions is minimal on purpose, and avoids defining `?` and `+`—these can be expressed as follows: `a+`=`aa*`, and `a?`=`(a|ε)`.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Sometimes the complement operator is added, to give a *generalized regular expression*; here *Rc* matches all strings over Σ* that do not match *R*.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] In principle, the complement operator is redundant, because it does not grant any more expressive power.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] However, it can make a regular expression much more concise—eliminating a single complement operator can cause a double exponential blow-up of its length.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions in this sense can express the regular languages, exactly the class of languages accepted by deterministic finite automata.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] There is, however, a significant difference in compactness.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Some classes of regular languages can only be described by deterministic finite automata whose size grows exponentially in the size of the shortest equivalent regular expressions.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The standard example here is the languages *Lk* consisting of all strings over the alphabet {*a*,*b*} whose *k*th-from-last letter equals *a*.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] On the one hand, a regular expression describing *L*4 is given by $(a\mid b)^{*}a(a\mid b)(a\mid b)(a\mid b)$ .
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] On the other hand, it is known that every deterministic finite automaton accepting the language *Lk* must have at least 2*k* states.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Luckily, there is a simple mapping from regular expressions to the more general nondeterministic finite automata (NFAs) that does not lead to such a blowup in size; for this reason NFAs are often used as alternative representations of regular languages.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] NFAs are a simple variation of the type-3 grammars of the Chomsky hierarchy.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] In the opposite direction, there are many languages easily described by a DFA that are not easily described by a regular expression.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] For instance, determining the validity of a given ISBN requires computing the remainder of an integer modulo 11, and can be easily implemented with an 11-state DFA.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] However, converting it to a regular expression results in a 2.14-megabyte file.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Given a regular expression, Thompson's construction algorithm computes an equivalent nondeterministic finite automaton.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] A conversion in the opposite direction is achieved by Kleene's algorithm.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Finally, many real-world "regular expression" engines implement features that cannot be described by the regular expressions in the sense of formal language theory; rather, they implement *regexes*.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] As seen in many of the examples above, there is more than one way to construct a regular expression to achieve the same results.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] It is possible to write an algorithm that, for two given regular expressions, decides whether the described languages are equal; the algorithm reduces each expression to a minimal deterministic finite state machine, and determines whether they are isomorphic (equivalent).
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] More generally, an equation *E*=*F* between regular-expression terms with variables holds if, and only if, its instantiation with different variables replaced by different symbol constants holds.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Every regular expression can be written solely in terms of the Kleene star and set unions over finite words.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] This is a surprisingly difficult problem.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] As simple as the regular expressions are, there is no method to systematically rewrite them to some normal form.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The lack of axiom in the past led to the star height problem.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] In 1991, Dexter Kozen axiomatized regular expressions as a Kleene algebra, using equational and Horn clause axioms.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Already in 1964, Redko had proved that no finite set of purely equational axioms can characterize the algebra of regular languages.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] A regex *pattern* matches a target *string*.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The pattern is composed of a sequence of *atoms*.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] An atom is a single point within the regex pattern which it tries to match to the target string.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The simplest atom is a literal, but grouping parts of the pattern to match an atom will require using `( )` as metacharacters.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] A match is made, not when all the atoms of the string are matched, but rather when all the pattern atoms in the regex have matched.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The idea is to make a small pattern of characters stand for a large number of possible strings, rather than compiling a large list of all the literal possibilities.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Depending on the regex processor there are about fourteen metacharacters, characters that may or may not have their literal character meaning, depending on context, or whether they are "escaped", i.e. preceded by an escape sequence, in this case, the backslash `\`.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The usual characters that become metacharacters when escaped are `dswDSW` and `N`.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] When entering a regex in a programming language, they may be represented as a usual string literal, hence usually quoted; this is common in C, Java, and Python for instance, where the regex `re` is entered as `"re"`.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] However, they are often written with slashes as delimiters, as in `/re/` for the regex `re`.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] A similar convention is used in sed, where search and replace is given by `s/re/replacement/` and patterns can be joined with a comma to specify a range of lines as in `/re1/,/re2/`.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] This notation is particularly well known due to its use in Perl, where it forms part of the syntax distinct from normal string literals.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] In some cases, such as sed and Perl, alternative delimiters can be used to avoid collision with contents, and to avoid having to escape occurrences of the delimiter character in the contents.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] For example, in sed the command `s,/,X,` will replace a `/` with an `X`, using commas as delimiters.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The IEEE POSIX standard has three sets of compliance: **BRE** (Basic Regular Expressions), **ERE** (Extended Regular Expressions), and **SRE** (Simple Regular Expressions).
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] SRE is deprecated, in favor of BRE, as both provide backward compatibility.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The subsection below covering the *character classes* applies to both BRE and ERE.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] ERE adds `?`, `+`, and `|`, and it removes the need to escape the metacharacters `( )` and `{ }`, which are *required* in BRE.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Furthermore, as long as the POSIX standard syntax for regexes is adhered to, there can be, and often is, additional syntax to serve specific (yet POSIX compliant) applications.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Although POSIX.2 leaves some implementation specifics undefined, BRE and ERE provide a "standard" which has since been adopted as the default syntax of many tools, where the choice of BRE or ERE modes is usually a supported option.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] For example, GNU `grep` has the following options: "`grep -E`" for ERE, and "`grep -G`" for BRE (the default), and "`grep -P`" for Perl regexes.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Perl regexes have become a de facto standard, having a rich and powerful set of atomic expressions.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Perl has no "basic" or "extended" levels.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] As in POSIX EREs, `( )` and `{ }` are treated as metacharacters unless escaped; other metacharacters are known to be literal or symbolic based on context alone.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Additional functionality includes lazy matching, backreferences, named capture groups, and recursive patterns.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] In the POSIX standard, Basic Regular Syntax (**BRE**) requires that the metacharacters `( )` and `{ }` be designated `\(\)` and `\{\}`, whereas Extended Regular Syntax (**ERE**) does not.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] According to Russ Cox, the POSIX specification requires ambiguous subexpressions to be handled in a way different from Perl's.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The committee replaced Perl's rules with one that is simple to explain, but the new "simple" rules are actually more complex to implement: they were incompatible with pre-existing tooling and made it essentially impossible to define a "lazy match" (see below) extension.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] As a result, very few programs actually implement the POSIX subexpression rules (even when they implement other parts of the POSIX syntax).
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The meaning of metacharacters escaped with a backslash is reversed for some characters in the POSIX Extended Regular Expression (**ERE**) syntax.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] With this syntax, a backslash causes the metacharacter to be treated as a literal character.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] POSIX Extended Regular Expressions can often be used with modern Unix utilities by including the command line flag *-E*.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The character class is the most basic regex concept after a literal match.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] It makes one small sequence of characters match a larger set of characters.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] For example, `[A-Z]` could stand for any uppercase letter in the English alphabet, and `\d` could mean any digit.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Character classes apply to both POSIX levels.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] When specifying a range of characters, such as `[a-Z]` (i.e. lowercase *`a`* to uppercase *`Z`*), the computer's locale settings determine the contents by the numeric ordering of the character encoding.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] They could store digits in that sequence, or the ordering could be *abc...zABC...Z*, or *aAbBcC...zZ*.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] So the POSIX standard defines a character class, which will be known by the regex processor installed.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] POSIX character classes can only be used within bracket expressions.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] For example, `[[:upper:]ab]` matches the uppercase letters and lowercase "a" and "b".
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] An additional non-POSIX class understood by some tools is `[:word:]`, which is usually defined as `[:alnum:]` plus underscore.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] This reflects the fact that in many programming languages these are the characters that may be used in identifiers.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Note that what the POSIX regex standards call *character classes* are commonly referred to as *POSIX character classes* in other regex flavors which support them.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] With most other regex flavors, the term *character class* is used to describe what POSIX calls *bracket expressions*.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Because of its expressive power and (relative) ease of reading, many other utilities and programming languages have adopted syntax similar to Perl's—for example, Java, JavaScript, Julia, Python, Ruby, Qt, Microsoft's .NET Framework, and XML Schema.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Some languages and tools such as Boost and PHP support multiple regex flavors.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Perl-derivative regex implementations are not identical and usually implement a subset of features found in Perl 5.0, released in 1994.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Perl sometimes does incorporate features initially found in other languages.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] For example, Perl 5.10 implements syntactic extensions originally developed in PCRE and Python.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] In Python and some other implementations (e.g.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Java), the three common quantifiers (`*`, `+`, and `?`) are greedy by default because they match as many characters as possible.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] matches the entire line (because the entire line begins and ends with a double-quote) instead of matching only the first part, `"Ganymede,"`.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The aforementioned quantifiers may, however, be made *lazy* or *minimal* or *reluctant*, matching as few characters as possible, by appending a question mark: `".+?"` matches only `"Ganymede,"`.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] matches the entire line, the regex `".*+"` does *not match at all*, because `.*+` consumes the entire input, including the final `"`.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Thus, possessive quantifiers are most useful with negated character classes, e.g.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] `"[^"]*+"`, which matches `"Ganymede,"` when applied to the same string.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Another common extension serving the same function is atomic grouping, which disables backtracking for a parenthesized group.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] For example, while ^(wi|w)i$ matches both wi and wii, ^(?>wi|w)i$ only matches wii because the engine is forbidden from backtracking and so cannot try setting the group to "w" after matching "wi".
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Possessive quantifiers are easier to implement than greedy and lazy quantifiers, and are typically more efficient at runtime.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] IETF RFC 9485 describes "I-Regexp: An Interoperable Regular Expression Format".
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] It specifies a limited subset of regular-expression idioms designed to be interoperable, i.e. produce the same effect, in a large number of regular-expression libraries.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] I-Regexp is also limited to matching, i.e. providing a true or false match between a regular expression and a given piece of text.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Thus, it lacks advanced features such as capture groups, lookahead, and backreferences.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Many features found in virtually all modern regular expression libraries provide an expressive power that exceeds the regular languages.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] For example, many implementations allow grouping subexpressions with parentheses and recalling the value they match in the same expression (*backreferences*).
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] This means that, among other things, a pattern can match strings of repeated words like "papa" or "WikiWiki", called *squares* in formal language theory.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The pattern for these strings is `(.+)\1`.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The language of squares is not regular, nor is it context-free, due to the pumping lemma.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] However, pattern matching with an unbounded number of backreferences, as supported by numerous modern tools, is still context sensitive.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The general problem of matching any number of backreferences is NP-complete, and the execution time for known algorithms grows exponentially by the number of backreference groups used.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] However, many tools, libraries, and engines that provide such constructions still use the term *regular expression* for their patterns.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] This has led to a nomenclature where the term regular expression has different meanings in formal language theory and pattern matching.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] For this reason, some people have taken to using the term *regex*, *regexp*, or simply *pattern* to describe the latter.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Other features not found in describing regular languages include assertions.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] These include the ubiquitous `^` and `$`, used since at least 1970, as well as some more sophisticated extensions like lookaround that appeared in 1994.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Lookarounds define the surrounding of a match and do not spill into the match itself, a feature only relevant for the use case of string searching.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Some of them can be simulated in a regular language by treating the surroundings as a part of the language as well.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The look-ahead assertions `(?=...)` and `(?!...)` have been attested since at least 1994, starting with Perl 5.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The lookbehind assertions `(?<=...)` and `(?<!...)` are attested since 1997 in a commit by Ilya Zakharevich to Perl 5.005.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] There are at least three different algorithms that decide whether and how a given regex matches a string.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The oldest and fastest relies on a result in formal language theory that allows every nondeterministic finite automaton (NFA) to be transformed into a deterministic finite automaton (DFA).
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The DFA can be constructed explicitly and then run on the resulting input string one symbol at a time.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Constructing the DFA for a regular expression of size *m* has the time and memory cost of *O*(2*m*), but it can be run on a string of size *n* in time *O*(*n*).
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Note that the size of the expression is the size after abbreviations, such as numeric quantifiers, have been expanded.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] An alternative approach is to simulate the NFA directly, essentially building each DFA state on demand and then discarding it at the next step.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] This keeps the DFA implicit and avoids the exponential construction cost, but running cost rises to *O*(*mn*).
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The explicit approach is called the DFA algorithm and the implicit approach the NFA algorithm.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Adding caching to the NFA algorithm is often called the "lazy DFA" algorithm, or just the DFA algorithm without making a distinction.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] These algorithms are fast, but using them for recalling grouped subexpressions, lazy quantification, and similar features is tricky.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Modern implementations include the re1-re2-sregex family based on Cox's code.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] The third algorithm is to match the pattern against the input string by backtracking.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] This algorithm is commonly called NFA, but this terminology can be confusing.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Its running time can be exponential, which simple implementations exhibit when matching against expressions like `(a|aa)*b` that contain both alternation and unbounded quantification and force the algorithm to consider an exponentially increasing number of sub-cases.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] This behavior can cause a security problem called Regular expression Denial of Service (ReDoS).
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Although backtracking implementations only give an exponential guarantee in the worst case, they provide much greater flexibility and expressive power.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] For example, any implementation which allows the use of backreferences, or implements the various extensions introduced by Perl, must include some kind of backtracking.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Some implementations try to provide the best of both algorithms by first running a fast DFA algorithm, and revert to a potentially slower backtracking algorithm only when a backreference is encountered during the match.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] GNU grep (and the underlying gnulib DFA) uses such a strategy.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Sublinear runtime algorithms have been achieved using Boyer-Moore (BM) based algorithms and related DFA optimization techniques such as the reverse scan.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] GNU grep, which supports a wide variety of POSIX syntaxes and extensions, uses BM for a first-pass prefiltering, and then uses an implicit DFA.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Wu agrep, which implements approximate matching, combines the prefiltering into the DFA in BDM (backward DAWG matching).
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] NR-grep's BNDM extends the BDM technique with Shift-Or bit-level parallelism.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] A few theoretical alternatives to backtracking for backreferences exist, and their "exponents" are tamer in that they are only related to the number of backreferences, a fixed property of some regexp languages such as POSIX.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] One naive method that duplicates a non-backtracking NFA for each backreference note has a complexity of ⁠ ${\mathrm {O} }(n^{2k+2})$ ⁠ time and ⁠ ${\mathrm {O} }(n^{2k+1})$ ⁠ space for a haystack of length n and k backreferences in the RegExp.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Theoretical work based on memory automata gives a tighter bound based on "active" variable nodes used, and a polynomial possibility for some backreferenced regexps.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] In theoretical terms, any token set can be matched by regular expressions as long as it is pre-defined.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] In terms of historical implementations, regexes were originally written to use ASCII characters as their token set though regex libraries have supported numerous other character sets.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Many modern regex engines offer at least some support for Unicode.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] In most respects it makes no difference what the character set is, but some issues do arise when extending regexes to support Unicode.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p01] Most general-purpose programming languages support regex capabilities, either natively or via libraries.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] Regexes are useful in a wide variety of text processing tasks, and more generally string processing, where the data need not be textual.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] Common applications include data validation, data scraping (especially web scraping), data wrangling, simple parsing, the production of syntax highlighting systems, and many other tasks.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] Some high-end desktop publishing software has the ability to use regexes to automatically apply text styling, saving the person doing the layout from laboriously doing this by hand for anything that can be matched by a regex.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] For example, by defining a character style that makes text into small caps and then using the regex `[A-Z]{4,}` to apply that style, any word of four or more consecutive capital letters will be automatically rendered as small caps instead.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] While regexes would be useful on Internet search engines, processing them across the entire database could consume excessive computer resources depending on the complexity and design of the regex.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] Although in many cases system administrators can run regex-based queries internally, most search engines do not offer regex support to the public.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] Notable exceptions include Google Code Search and Exalead.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] However, Google Code Search was shut down in January 2012.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] The specific syntax rules vary depending on the specific implementation, programming language, or library in use.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] Additionally, the functionality of regex implementations can vary between versions.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] Because regexes can be difficult to both explain and understand without examples, interactive websites for testing regexes are a useful resource for learning regexes by experimentation.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] This section provides a basic description of some of the properties of regexes by way of illustration.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] The following conventions are used in the examples.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] Standard POSIX regular expressions are different.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] Unless otherwise indicated, the following examples conform to the Perl programming language, release 5.8.8, January 31, 2006.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] This means that other implementations may lack support for some parts of the syntax shown here (e.g. basic vs. extended regex, `\( \)` vs.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] The syntax and conventions used in these examples coincide with that of other programming environments as well.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] Regular expressions can often be created ("induced" or "learned") based on a set of example strings.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] This is known as the induction of regular languages and is part of the general problem of grammar induction in computational learning theory.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] Formally, given examples of strings in a regular language, and perhaps also given examples of strings *not* in that regular language, it is possible to induce a grammar for the language, i.e., a regular expression that generates that language.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] Not all regular languages can be induced in this way (see language identification in the limit), but many can.
[src:regex/regular-expression-p02] For example, the set of examples {1, 10, 100}, and negative set (of counterexamples) {11, 1001, 101, 0} can be used to induce the regular expression 1⋅0* (1 followed by zero or more 0s).
[src:regex/regular-expressions-quantifiers] Quantifiers indicate numbers of characters or expressions to match.
[src:regex/regular-expressions-quantifiers] In this example, we match one or more word characters with `\w+`, then one or more characters "a" with `a+`, and finally end at a word boundary with `\b`.
[src:regex/regular-expressions-quantifiers] In this example, we match words that have a single letter, words that have between 2 and 6 letters, and words that have 13 or more letters.
[src:regex/regular-expressions-quantifiers] In this example, we match words that either end with "our" or "or".
[src:regex/regular-expressions-quantifiers] In this example, we match one or more word characters or spaces with `[\w ]+` and `[\w ]+?`.
[src:regex/regular-expressions-quantifiers] The first one is greedy and the second one is non-greedy.
[src:regex/regular-expressions-quantifiers] Note how the second one stops as soon as it meets the minimal requirement.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] Regular expressions are patterns used to match character combinations in strings.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] In JavaScript, regular expressions are also objects.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] These patterns are used with the `exec()` and `test()` methods of `RegExp`, and with the `match()`, `matchAll()`, `replace()`, `replaceAll()`, `search()`, and `split()` methods of `String`.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] This chapter describes JavaScript regular expressions.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] It provides a brief overview of each syntax element.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] For a detailed explanation of each one's semantics, read the regular expressions reference.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] A regular expression pattern is composed of simple characters, such as `/abc/`, or a combination of simple and special characters, such as `/ab*c/` or `/Chapter (\d+)\.\d*/`.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] The last example includes parentheses, which are used as a memory device.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] The match made with this part of the pattern is remembered for later use, as described in Using groups.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] Simple patterns are constructed of characters for which you want to find a direct match.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] For example, the pattern `/abc/` matches character combinations in strings only when the exact sequence `"abc"` occurs (all characters together and in that order).
[src:regex/regular-expressions] Such a match would succeed in the strings `"Hi, do you know your abc's?"` and `"The latest airplane designs evolved from slabcraft."`.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] In both cases the match is with the substring `"abc"`.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] There is no match in the string `"Grab crab"` because while it contains the substring `"ab c"`, it does not contain the exact substring `"abc"`.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] When the search for a match requires something more than a direct match, such as finding one or more b's, or finding white space, you can include special characters in the pattern.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] For example, to match *a single `"a"` followed by zero or more `"b"`s followed by `"c"`*, you'd use the pattern `/ab*c/`: the `*` after `"b"` means "0 or more occurrences of the preceding item." In the string `"cbbabbbbcdebc"`, this pattern will match the substring `"abbbbc"`.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] The following pages provide lists of the different special characters that fit into each category, along with descriptions and examples.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] Assertions include boundaries, which indicate the beginnings and endings of lines and words, and other patterns indicating in some way that a match is possible (including look-ahead, look-behind, and conditional expressions).
[src:regex/regular-expressions] Distinguish different types of characters.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] For example, distinguishing between letters and digits.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] Indicate numbers of characters or expressions to match.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] If you need to use any of the special characters literally (actually searching for a `"*"`, for instance), you should escape it by putting a backslash in front of it.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] For instance, to search for `"a"` followed by `"*"` followed by `"b"`, you'd use `/a\*b/` — the backslash "escapes" the `"*"`, making it literal instead of special.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] Similarly, if you're writing a regular expression literal and need to match a slash ("/"), you need to escape that (otherwise, it terminates the pattern).
[src:regex/regular-expressions] For instance, to search for the string "/example/" followed by one or more alphabetic characters, you'd use `/\/example\/[a-z]+/i`—the backslashes before each slash make them literal.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] To match a literal backslash, you need to escape the backslash.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] For instance, to match the string "C:\" where "C" can be any letter, you'd use `/[A-Z]:\\/` — the first backslash escapes the one after it, so the expression searches for a single literal backslash.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] If using the `RegExp` constructor with a string literal, remember that the backslash is an escape in string literals, so to use it in the regular expression, you need to escape it at the string literal level.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] `/a\*b/` and `new RegExp("a\\*b")` create the same expression, which searches for "a" followed by a literal "*" followed by "b".
[src:regex/regular-expressions] The `RegExp.escape()` function returns a new string where all special characters in regex syntax are escaped.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] This allows you to do `new RegExp(RegExp.escape("a*b"))` to create a regular expression that matches only the string `"a*b"`.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] Parentheses around any part of the regular expression pattern causes that part of the matched substring to be remembered.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] Once remembered, the substring can be recalled for other use.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] See Groups and backreferences for more details.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] Regular expressions are used with the `RegExp` methods `test()` and `exec()` and with the `String` methods `match()`, `matchAll()`, `replace()`, `replaceAll()`, `search()`, and `split()`.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] When you want to know whether a pattern is found in a string, use the `test()` or `search()` methods; for more information (but slower execution) use the `exec()` or `match()` methods.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] If you use `exec()` or `match()` and if the match succeeds, these methods return an array and update properties of the associated regular expression object and also of the predefined regular expression object, `RegExp`.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] If the match fails, the `exec()` method returns `null` (which coerces to `false`).
[src:regex/regular-expressions] In the following example, the script uses the `exec()` method to find a match in a string.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] With these scripts, the match succeeds and returns the array and updates the properties shown in the following table.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] As shown in the second form of this example, you can use a regular expression created with an object initializer without assigning it to a variable.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] If you do, however, every occurrence is a new regular expression.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] For this reason, if you use this form without assigning it to a variable, you cannot subsequently access the properties of that regular expression.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] The occurrences of `/d(b+)d/g` in the two statements are different regular expression objects and hence have different values for their `lastIndex` property.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] If you need to access the properties of a regular expression created with an object initializer, you should first assign it to a variable.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] Regular expressions have optional flags that allow for functionality like global searching and case-insensitive searching.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] These flags can be used separately or together in any order, and are included as part of the regular expression.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] Note that the flags are an integral part of a regular expression.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] For example, `re = /\w+\s/g` creates a regular expression that looks for one or more characters followed by a space, and it looks for this combination throughout the string.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] The `m` flag is used to specify that a multiline input string should be treated as multiple lines.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] If the `m` flag is used, `^` and `$` match at the start or end of any line within the input string instead of the start or end of the entire string.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] The `i`, `m`, and `s` flags can be enabled or disabled for specific parts of a regex using the modifier syntax.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] `RegExp.prototype.exec()` method with the `g` flag returns each match and its position iteratively.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] In contrast, `String.prototype.match()` method returns all matches at once, but without their position.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] The `u` flag is used to create "unicode" regular expressions; that is, regular expressions which support matching against unicode text.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] An important feature that's enabled in unicode mode is Unicode property escapes.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] Unicode regular expressions have different execution behavior as well.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] `RegExp.prototype.unicode` contains more explanation about this.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] In the following example, the user is expected to enter a phone number.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] When the user presses the "Check" button, the script checks the validity of the number.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] If the number is valid (matches the character sequence specified by the regular expression), the script shows a message thanking the user and confirming the number.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] If the number is invalid, the script informs the user that the phone number is not valid.
[src:regex/regular-expressions] An online tool to learn, build, & test Regular Expressions.
